Executive Summary | Respiratory Disease Data Analysis

This report investigates factors associated with the risk of respiratory diseases in infants and build a risk prediction model to estimate the probability of an infant developing respiratory disease.

Introduction

The dataset Training.csv consists of 18,422 infants from 40 countries. 8 variables are investigated which are listed below:

  1. status (status respiratory disease) Metric: 0 (No), 1 (Yes)

  2. gender Metric: F (Female), M (Male)

  3. fed_method: feeding methods Metric: 4 categories (breastfeed only, bottle feed only, mix bottle and breast feed, supplement only)

  4. sleep_hour: average number of sleeping hours

  5. delivery_type: type of delivery Metric: 0 (Natural Birth), 1 (Cesarean birth)

  6. weight: weight of mother before pregnancy Metric: 0 (Underweight), 1 (Normal Weight)

  7. smoking: smoking status of mother before pregnancy Metric: N (No), Y (Yes)

  8. diabetes: mother with gestational diabetes Metric: N (No). Y (Yes)

  9. API: air pollution index Metric: 0-50: good, 51-100: moderate, 101-200: unhealthy, 201-300: very unhealthy, >300: hazardous

Additionally, we have checked that the data set contains no missing data. Therefore, we can proceed to exploratory analyses.

Chi-squared test will be used to assess whether there is difference between respiratory status for each of the factors (excluding smoking) in the Training.csv data set. The factors that will be analysed includes: API, weight, gender, fed_method, delivery_type,and diabetes.

Prior to using chi-squared distribution, several assumptions need to be fulfilled:

  1. All observations are independent: this assumption is fulfilled as each infants respiratory status does not affect another infants respiratory status.
  2. The levels of the categorical variables are mutually exclusive: As seen within the Training.csv data set, each infant fits to only one level of each of the categorical variables.

Chi-Square test to determine difference between status of respiratory for each variables of Interest:

\(H_0\): infants gender and respiratory status are independent

\(H_1\): infants gender and respiratory status are dependent

#gender
cont_table0 <- table(training$status,training$gender)
chisq.test(cont_table0)

Conclusion of the Chi-Square Test :

Based on chi-square test, at a 5% significance level, variables that have difference based on the infants respiratory status are: weight, API, diabetes, sleep_hour and delivery_type. Therefore we can reject the null hypothesis \(H_0\) for these variables.

Additionally, for sleep_hour we have to conduct a t-test as it is a continuous variable. Prior to doing t-test, we must check for normality assumptions.

  1. All observations are independent: this assumption is fulfilled as each infants respiratory status is not affected by another infants

  2. Normality: we will check this assumption by drawing up the QQ-plot

qqnorm(training$sleep_hour, pch = 1, frame = FALSE)
qqline(training$sleep_hour,col = "steelblue", lwd = 2)

Based on the QQ plot, we can safely assume that sleep_hour is normally distributed as most of the data points fall approximately to the reference line. We may proceed to using the t-test to determine if there are any difference between sleep_hour and status.

T-test Between Status and Sleep_Hour

\(H_0\): \(\mu_A= \mu_B\) \(H_1\): \(\mu_A\neq \mu_B\)

where \(A\) represents sleep_hour with status = 0 (infant does not have respiratory disease) and \(B\) represents sleep_hour with status=1 (infant has respiratory disease)

#sleep_hour T-Test

respiratory_status_0 <- subset(training, status == 0)
respiratory_status_1 <- subset(training, status == 1)

# Conduct a two-sample t-test

t.test(respiratory_status_0$sleep_hour, respiratory_status_1$sleep_hour)
##

Based on the t-test output, the p-value shown is 0.05878 which is greater than the 5% significance level. Therefore sleep_hour does not show any difference based on the infants different status . Additionally, the 95% confidence interval from the t.test() command reflects the same result as with looking at the p-value.

In summary, variables that have shown any difference towards an infants status are: weight, API, diabetes, sleep_hour and delivery_type.

Assumption of Generalised Linear Model

Each infant recorded in the data set is a binary variable (status = 0 if infant does not have respiratory disease or 1 if infant does have respiratory disease ). The structure of the data set suggest the model to be a binomial distribution: \(Y_i\) ~ \(Bin(n_i,p_i)\), where \(p_i\) is the probability of an infant developing the respiratory disease. Binomial distribution is appropriate as the outcome of the each infant in this data set could take one of two values which are 1 (indicating infant has the respiratory disease) and 0 (indicating the infant does not have respiratory disease) based on the records of 1824 infants. We will proceed to using logistic regression model based on datasets binomial distribution.

Checking linear assumption in the case of logistic regression

To satisfy the linear assumption for logistic regression, we need to check the linear relationship visually between the continuous predictor variable sleep_hour and the logit of the infants status.

# fit logistic regression model
model <- glm(status~gender+fed_method+sleep_hour+API+diabetes+delivery_type+weight, data = training, 
               family = binomial)

ggplot(training, aes(x = sleep_hour, y = log(model$fitted.values / (1 - model$fitted.values)))) +
  geom_jitter() +
  xlab("Sleep Hour") +
  ylab("Log Odds of Status")

Based on the scatter plot above, sleep_hour is linearly associated with infants log odds status. Therefore, we may proceed to model selection as linearity assumption for logistic regression is satisfied.

Model Fitting

For the subsequent model fitting, we will categorize the average sleeping hour into 3 groups: <11.6 hours, 11.6-12.9 hours, and >12.9 hours.

training$sleep_hour <- cut(training$sleep_hour, breaks = c(-Inf, 11.6, 12.9, Inf), 
                  labels = c("<11.6 hours", ">11.6-12.9 hours", ">12.9 hours"),
                  right = FALSE, include.lowest = TRUE)

Final Model

Based on the R output above, status ~ diabetes + sleep_hour + delivery_type + API + weight + fed_method is the best model as it has the lowest AIC value of \(23389.1\).

Final Prediction Model:

\(log(\frac{p}{1-p}) = -1+0.096a_i+0.094b_{i1}+0.29b_{i2}+0.14c_i + 0.099d_{i1}+0.15d_{i2} +0.21d_{i3} + 0.23d_{i4} - 0.08e_{i} + 0.09f_{i1} - 0.14f_{i2} + 0.08f_{i3}\)

where:

  • \(a_i\) = 1 if diabetes = Yes, else 0

  • \(b_{i1}\) = 1 if sleep_hour is 11.6-12.9 hours,else 0

  • \(b_{i2}\) =1 if sleep_hour >12.9 hours, else 0

  • \(c_i\) =1 if delivery_type is cesarean, else 0

  • \(d_{i1}\) = 1 if API 51-100, else 0

  • \(d_{i2}\) = 1 if API 101-200, else 0

  • \(d_{i3}\) = 1 if API 201-300, else 0

  • \(d_{i4}\) = 1 if API >300, else 0

  • \(e_i\) = 1 if weight is normal, else 0

  • \(f_{i1}\)= 1 if fed_method is bottle feed only, else 0

  • \(f_{i2}\) = 1 if fed_method is mix bottle, else 0

  • \(f_{i3}\) = 1 if fed_method is supplement only, else 0

Results Table

P-value

Based on the p-value output in the output above, we observe that diabetes,sleep_hour>12.9, delivery_type1,API>300,API101-200,API201-300,weight,fed_methodSupplement are smaller than the 5% significance level. Therefore we can conlude that these variables are important variables to consider in predicting an infants respiratory status.

95% Confidence Interval Based on the Odds Ratio:

Based on the 95% confidence interval on the odds ratio, we can observe that diabetes= Yes, sleep_hour>12.9 hours,delivery_type=1, API (101-200,201-300,>300), weight and fed_method$Supplement to be statistically significant at the 5% level as the 95% confidence intervals for these variables did not include 1. Therefore these variables have a strong association with the response variable status. In other words, infants possessing the variables mentioned have a higher risk of developing respiratory disease. The result of the 95% confidence interval reflects the same results as with the p-value.

Odds Ratio of Final Model:

Based on the odds ratio above,

  1. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease with normal weight mothers is (1-0.9216815=0.078) 7.8% lower compared to infants with underweight mothers.

  2. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is (1.1535730) 15% higher for infants delivered by cesarean section than normal birth.

  3. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is (1.1010036) 10.1% higher for infants who have mothers with gestational diabetes compared to mothers who do not have gestational diabetes.

  4. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is (1.2546963) 25.4% higher for infants living in air pollution index of >300, and (1.1595934) 15.9% higher for infants living in air pollution index of 101-200, (1.2328598) 23.2% higher for infants living in air pollution index of 201-300, (1.1043857) 10.4% higher for infants living in air pollution index of 51-100 compared to infants living in air pollution index below 50.

  5. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is (1-0.8673263=0.1326) 13.26% times lower for infants being fed with mix of bottle and breastfeed, (1.0946860) 9.46% higher for infants with bottle feed only, (1.0827051) 8.27% higher for infants fed with supplement only compared to infants who breastfeed only.

  6. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is 33% higher for infants sleeping greater than 12.9 hours and the odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is 9.9% higher for infants sleeping between 11.6-12.9 hours compared to infants who slept less than 11.6 hours.

Summary

In this report, we have investigated which factors are significant based on the infants status and built a prediction model to estimate the risk of an infant developing respiratory disease. Based on our prediction model, we have concluded that fed_method, diabetes, sleep_hour, delivery_type, API,and weight are important variables to consider in investigating whether an infant is likely to develop respiratory disease.

We have found no evidence that suggest that gender plays a significant role in determining whether an infant is likely to develop respiratory disease based on the chi-square test and during the model development. Additionally, smoking variable plays no role in the model development as all mothers in this data set did not smoke prior to their pregnancy. Below are all the main findings of each of the important variables:

Detailed Summary of the Important Factors Impacting the Odds of Infants Developing Respiratory Disease

Respiratory Status and Delivery_Type: Our findings show that large proportion of infants from both respiratory status are delivered by natural birth which was shown in the exploratory analyses table. We investigated delivery_type using chi-square test which indicated there exist differences between status of infant and delivery_type. Based on the prediction model, we found that infants delivered by cesarean section to be statistically significant at the 5% significance level and infants who are delivered by cesarean section have higher risk in developing respiratory disease by 15% compared to infants from normal birth. Therefore, delivery_type has a great impact on whether an infant develops respiratory disease.

Respiratory Status and Diabetes : Our findings show a large proportion of infants from both respiratory status have mothers with gestational diabetes. We investigated the significance of diabetes using the chi-square tests and have found that there exists difference between infants status and diabetes. Based on the prediction model , we discovered that infants who have mothers with gestational diabetes are at risk of developing respiratory disease by 10.1% higher compared to infants who do not have mothers with gestational diabetes

Respiratory Status and Sleep_Hour: Our findings based on the chi-square test show that there is significant difference between infants status and sleep_hour. Based on the prediction model, we discovered that infants who have sleep_hour > 12.9 hours to be statistically significant at the 5% level and is at risk of developing respiratory disease by 13.26% compared with infants with sleep_hour <11.6. Infants with sleep_hour between 11.6-12.9 hours was not shown to be statistically significant at the 5% level.

Respiratory Status and Weight: Our exploratory analysis have shown that large proportion of infants from both respiratory status have normal weight (weight=1). Based on the chi-square test, we discovered that there is difference between infants status and weight. The prediction model shows that weight is an important variable to consider as it is statistically significant at the 5% level. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is 7.86% lower for normal weight mothers compared to underweight mothers

Respiratory Status and API: Our exploratory analysis show that most infants from both respiratory status live in air pollution index (API) between 101-200. Based on the chi-square tset, we discovered that there exist difference between infants status and API. The model development also shows that API is an important variable to consider specifically, for API>300, API: 101-200, and API: 201-300 at the 5% significance level. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is 25.5% higher for infants living in API of >300 compared to infants living in API < 50. The odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is 16% higher for infants living in air pollution index of 101-200 and 23.3% higher for infants living in API 201-300 compared to infants living in API < 50.

Respiratory Status and Feeding method: Our exploratory analysis show that most infants from both respiratory status are fed by supplement only. Based on the chi-square test, we discovered that there exist difference between an infants status and fed_method. The prediction model shows that fed_method to be an important variable to consider specifically for infants who are fed with supplements only at the 5% significance level. In conclusion, the odds of an infant developing respiratory disease is 8.27% higher for infants who are fed with supplements compared to infants who are fed breastfeed only.

Limitation of Analysis

Inclusion of other factor variables such as premature birth, inclusion of maternal smoking and genetic factors could help in improving the model prediction and increase the model accuracy. Currently, the model prediction accurately predicts 66.67% of known infants respiratory status on the Testing data set. This level of accuracy is insufficient as using this current risk prediction model could cause large number of infants to not receive preventive interventions.

Probability of an infant developing respiratory disease within their first month after birth:

The fitted model explained above would not be appropriate to determine the probability of an infant developing respiratory disease within their first month after birth. A suitable model to answer this question would be to use survival analysis. Data collection of censored infants (e.g.left censoring: infants who have developed the respiratory disease before trial, right censoring: infant has not developed respiratory disease by the time of trial) needs to be collected. Specifically, a cox model would be appropriate to use in identifying the probability of an infant developing respiratory disease within their first month after birth.
